claim: Vaccination with a higher-dose recombinant flu vaccine may induce a more robust antibody response than egg-based standard-dose vaccines.
explanation: A table comparing vaccine effectiveness (VE) percentages (with 95% confidence intervals) for recombinant influenza vaccine (RIV4) versus standard-dose egg-based quadrivalent inactivated vaccine (SD-IIV4) in two age groups (18–64 years and ≥65 years), with additional columns for HD-IIV4 and adjuvanted IIV in the ≥65 group. Evidence: For 18–64 year olds, RIV4 shows VE 47% (35–56) versus SD-IIV4 VE 27% (8–42); for ≥65 year olds, RIV4 VE 27% (12–39) versus SD-IIV4 VE 9% (–42–42). The table provides comparative clinical effectiveness data, not antibody response measurements, so it does not support the claim. Note: The table is clear but presents VE data rather than immunogenicity or antibody titers, limiting direct relevance to the claim about antibody response.
